        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><hi rend="underline"><placeName>Macon Geo.</placeName> <date>March 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#47;49</date></hi></p>
			<p>Rev Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I trust <sic>ze</sic> object of my letter will be a<lb/> sufficient excuse for <sic>ze</sic> liberty I take in address<lb/>&#45;ing you. In preparing a paper for publication<lb/> on <add>the&#63;</add> &#8220;Original Units of <sic>ze</sic> American Race&#44;&#8221; I have met<lb/> <sic>ze</sic> following objection advanced in a review of <persName>Dr<lb/> Pritchard&#39;s</persName> work on &#8220;<sic>ze</sic> natural History of Man&#8221;&#8212;<lb/> <sic>Ze</sic> reviewer says&#44; &#8220;According to <sic>ze</sic> Mosaic account <del>of</del><lb/> as generally interpreted it was necessary&#44; for <sic>ze</sic><lb/> continuance of <sic>ze</sic> human race&#44; that <persName>Adam&#39;s</persName> sons<lb/> should cohabit with their sisters. But that was<lb/> incest&#44; against which <sic>ze</sic> punishment of death was<lb/> afterwards &#40;&#33;&#41; proclaimed by <persName>Moses</persName> himself&#44; as I<lb/> express command of <sic>ze</sic> Deity&#8221; It is very evident that<lb/> <sic>ze</sic> author &#40;<persName>Dr Caldwell</persName>&#41; has here advanced a weak<lb/> &#38; absurd proposition&#58; for that which was unlaw<lb/>&#45;ful after <persName>Moses</persName> had received <sic>ze</sic> command&#45;<lb/>&#45;ments was certainly lawful previous to that<lb/> event. If members of <sic>ze</sic> same family did&#44; as<lb/> it is useless to deny&#44; cohabit&#44; they received <add>&#63;</add><lb/> Creator&#39;s blessing &#38; command to multiply &#38; replen&#45;<lb/>&#45;ish <sic>ze</sic> Earth. So with <persName>Noah</persName>. So with Sat.<lb/> But it is useless for me appeal to <sic>ze</sic> instances<lb/> of proof in <sic>ze</sic> scripture. They will at once<lb/> suggest themselves to <hi rend="underline">your</hi> mind. What I desire<lb/> is a more definite knowledge of <sic>ze</sic> view taken</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>of this subject by <sic>ze</sic> learned Jewish commen&#45;<lb/>&#45;tators. I appeal to you&#44; Rev Sir&#44; as one thorough<lb/>&#45;ly acquainted with Jewish literature &#38; whom<lb/> studies &#38; researches have qualified him&#44; not<lb/> more for <sic>ze</sic> profound philosopher than <sic>ze</sic><lb/> erudite metaply<add>&#63;</add>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I enclose this to you<lb/> under cover of my friend <persName>Dessan&#39;s</persName> epistle&#44; who<lb/> will bespeak for mine a favorable reception.</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I am&#44; dear Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">your very obt svt</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">C. T. Quintard M.D.</persName></p>
			<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>To <sic>ze</sic></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(3)"><placeName><hi rend="underline">Pa</hi></placeName></p>

          
